snippet.textDisplay:
I had instructors and professors like this.   But even the best professors ran into similar problems that required their teaching style to be roughed up: Depending on the level of class (if students were majoring or not in the subject) students' eyes would often glaze over, and during quizzes or questions the teacher would need to slow down, or repeat the lecture in a very jerky fashion, often running out of time and rushing through content in order to at least make it the test, paper, or final.  
Higher level courses, they move through subjects roughly as quick as this guy did, sometimes even quicker; thus making time for practical experiments, demonstrations, reviews, and moving on to more content.  


And some classes are literally bullshit classes; either the subject is too vague or the teacher doesn't like or understand the subject matter.... filler courses to make the school more money honey.... they and you know what classes I'm talking about.
  Fortunately for myself, I had very few those teachers or conditions in which the class was not so great.  The worst was taking tests on content we hadn't gone over yet, and nothing we did go over and told to study and read was on the test.  And the teacher on every test realizing this as students would ask him, and he'd either have to hint a few answers or give a few just so we could pass the class; particularly if you never took any prior weather/meteorology classes.   Was glad I had, it helped a little, but those tests were still pretty stormy. 



I thought this guy was excellent too.
But wait for the test at the end of the lesson. ;)~
